      Non-LBO
   =20
 =20

There is an important time lag in the financing of a leveraged buyout:
=09At Time 1, a private equity firm signs a deal to buy a company with borr=
owed money. The private equity firm works with some banks, who will get it =
the=C2=A0debt financing it needs to pay for the company.=09Months pass, as =
the deal gets shareholder and regulatory approvals, and as the banks market=
 the debt to investors (hedge funds, asset managers, and other people who b=
uy LBO debt). Eventually, at Time 2, the deal closes (the private equity fi=
rm actually buys the company), and the banks get the money from the debt in=
vestors and deliver it to the buyer.=C2=A0

The issue is that the debt market might change between Time 1 and Time 2. I=
f the debt market is very good at Time 1, and very bad at Time 2, then ther=
e is a problem: The private equity firm agreed to buy the company using bor=
rowed money, and it could borrow as much money as it needed at favorable ra=
tes in the debt market of Time 1, but in the debt markets of Time 2 it can=
=E2=80=99t borrow that much money at those rates, and the deal no longer ma=
kes=C2=A0sense, or at least not at the same price.
This is a risk, and it has to be allocated. You could imagine allocating th=
e risk to the buyer (it signs the deal at Time 1, and then has to accept wh=
atever the cost of debt is at Time 2), or to the seller (it signs the deal =
at Time 1, and then if the financing doesn=E2=80=99t work at Time 2 the buy=
er can walk away), or to the ultimate debt investors (the banks sell the de=
bt immediately at Time 1, and then if the market crashes the people who bou=
ght the debt lose money).
  [1]

But in practice this risk is mostly allocated to the banks.
  [2]
=C2=A0At Time 1, the banks give the buyer (and the company) signed debt com=
mitment letters, promising to lend the money that the buyer needs to buy th=
e company. If the debt markets freeze up at Time 2 and the banks can=E2=80=
=99t sell the debt, that=E2=80=99s their problem; they lend the money anywa=
y and are stuck holding the debt. Also, the commitment letters will general=
ly specify the approximate=C2=A0terms=C2=A0of the debt, things like how muc=
h secured and unsecured debt there will be, what sorts of maturities, and a=
t what interest rates; the banks will have some room to =E2=80=9Cflex=E2=80=
=9D the terms to respond to market conditions (i.e., the buyer will bear so=
me of the risk), but not too much. If the banks agree to lend at Time 1 at =
a maximum interest rate of 8%, and by Time 2 they can=E2=80=99t sell the de=
bt at a yield of less than 11%, that=E2=80=99s their problem. The debt gets=
 issued to the banks with an 8% interest rate, and they turn around and sel=
l it to investors at 85 cents on the dollar so it will yield 11%.
  [3]
=C2=A0The banks took the risk of the market getting worse, and they lost=C2=
=A015% on the deal.
  [4]

This is a common story, and the market for leveraged loans has crashed rece=
ntly, so this story is on a lot of people=E2=80=99s minds. We   have talked=
=C2=A0about the leveraged buyout of=C2=A0Citrix Systems Inc., which was sig=
ned in January and closed last month. The market was good in January and ba=
d in September, so the banks who committed to finance the Citrix deal   los=
t about $600 million on the deal. And we have talked a lot about Elon Musk=
=E2=80=99s deal to buy Twitter Inc., which was signed in April, is supposed=
 to   close next week (!?!), and has $13 billion of committed debt financin=
g, which will also cost Musk=E2=80=99s banks   hundreds of millions of doll=
ars of losses.
But there are other ways it can go. The debt market can be bad at Time 1 an=
d then good at Time 2, for instance. What if you are a private equity firm =
looking to sign up a leveraged buyout=C2=A0today?=C2=A0Today, the debt mark=
et is rough: Interest rates have gone up, credit has gotten worse, and bank=
s, nursing losses from Citrix and Twitter, are not all that jazzed about gi=
ving you committed financing on attractive terms. What do you do?
One option is to stop doing leveraged buyouts: LBOs are a product of easy c=
redit markets, and when credit gets more expensive there will be fewer LBOs=
. Another option is to just=C2=A0wait=C2=A0to do the LBO and see if credit =
markets come back.=C2=A0But if you really want to do this LBO today, you ca=
n sign up the LBO and=C2=A0not=C2=A0lock in financing on today=E2=80=99s te=
rms. You=E2=80=99re committed to pay for the company, but you=E2=80=99ll wa=
it to get financing. Maybe the debt market will get better.
Here are   Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Davide Scigliuzzo and Michelle Davis:

Long maligned as the debt-addicted corporate raiders of Wall Street, privat=
e equity firms are resorting to an unusual maneuver to get deals done as bo=
rrowing costs spiral. They=E2=80=99re taking the leverage out of leveraged =
buyouts.
Francisco Partners, Thoma Bravo and Stonepeak Partners are among those that=
 announced new acquisitions in recent weeks without debt financing in place=
, effectively backstopping the entire purchase price -- in some cases worth=
 north of $2 billion -- with cash from their own funds.
Though likely temporary, the all-equity move is a dramatic departure for an=
 industry famously hooked on leverage and constantly on the hunt for ever-m=
ore creative ways to boost returns.
Some of the firms held lending discussions with banks and private credit pr=
oviders, but they ultimately deemed the terms they were offered unattractiv=
e, according to people with knowledge of the matter, who asked not to be id=
entified because they=E2=80=99re not authorized to speak publicly.
The sponsors may ultimately replace some of the equity with loans or bonds =
at a later date. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CSponsors want maximum flexibility,=E2=80=9D said Richard Farley, a=
 partner at Kramer Levin Naftalis & Frankel LLP who works on buyout financi=
ngs. =E2=80=9CThey don=E2=80=99t want to be locked into very expensive debt=
 if they think they are going to have access to the debt market at more att=
ractive rates in a short period of time.=E2=80=9D

Obviously the risk is that the market gets even worse. But it=E2=80=99s bad=
 now, so it=E2=80=99s tempting to bet it will get better.

