If you go on  CoinMarketCap.com, it will tell you that =E2=80=9Cthe global =
crypto market cap is $923.36B,=E2=80=9D as of about 9:30 this morning. As w=
ith any index-y data provider, there are subjective choices being made ther=
e about exactly what and how to count. But  here is a Wired story about a g=
uy whose =E2=80=9Cown [crypto] balance exceeds five trillion dollars,=E2=80=
=9D which =E2=80=A6=C2=A0seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0high? He has roughly five tim=
es as much crypto as there is crypto. Clearly CoinMarketCap is not counting=
 his stash.
Oh, no, I=E2=80=99m kidding, you know how this joke goes. This is the hoary=
 old joke about how =E2=80=9Cmarket capitalization,=E2=80=9D in crypto =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and really in stocks, too =E2=80=94=C2=A0is=C2=A0fake, or at le=
ast=C2=A0potentially=C2=A0fake. It goes like this:
=09Anyone can make up a cryptocurrency and =E2=80=9Cprint=E2=80=9D as much =
of it as they want, trivially, for free. So I can make up Mattcoin,=C2=A0cr=
eate 5 trillion Mattcoins, and give them all to myself.=09Then I sell you o=
ne Mattcoin for $1. You pay me $1 for a Mattcoin because you=E2=80=99re my =
friend, or because it=E2=80=99s funny, or because I asked you to and Venmo=
=E2=80=99d you $5 and told you to keep the change. (Or, it being crypto, =
=E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=9D are just another anonymous wallet that I created myse=
lf, and I sell myself one Mattcoin for $1 in two different wallets.)=09Now =
the last reported trading price of Mattcoin is $1, you have one Mattcoin =
=E2=80=9Cworth=E2=80=9D $1, and I have 4,999,999,999,999 Mattcoins =E2=80=
=9Cworth,=E2=80=9D in round numbers, $5 trillion.=09Huzzah, market cap.

This joke generally ends with one of two punchlines:
=09Obviously Mattcoin isn=E2=80=99t worth $5 trillion and this is all stupi=
d, a reductio ad absurdum of reported crypto market caps;=C2=A0or
=09Now I=C2=A0tell=C2=A0people that Mattcoin really is worth $5 trillion. =
=E2=80=9CLook at this fast-growing Mattcoin ecosystem,=E2=80=9D I tell them=
, =E2=80=9Cit is already worth $5 trillion, but you can still get in at a g=
ood price, I=E2=80=99ll sell you 1 million Mattcoins for just $300,000, tha=
t=E2=80=99s a huge discount.=E2=80=9D Take some fake sales, add some intern=
et hype and sales patter, and see if I can turn them into real sales.

The second punchline is called =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulation.=E2=80=9D The f=
irst punchline is just =E2=80=9Clook how dumb this is.=E2=80=9D
Anyway here=E2=80=99s the guy in Wired:

His name is Valentin Broeksmit. =E2=80=A6 A musician and founder of a band =
called Bikini Robot Army, in press shots he affected the indie-singer look =
as a lanky man in his forties wearing shades and a fedora. His real claim t=
o fame, however, was as a financial whistleblower. In 2014, after the death=
 of his father, Deutsche Bank executive William Broeksmit, Broeksmit Jr. be=
gan to leak a trove of documents on the bank=E2=80=99s inner workings to jo=
urnalists and FBI agents. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
During his research, Broeksmit chanced upon Incognito Wallet, which develop=
ed a blockchain where people can exchange and trade cryptocurrencies via pe=
er-to-peer payments or through a decentralized exchange (DEX), which allows=
 cryptocurrencies to be swapped directly without going through intermediari=
es. Run by an anonymous team mostly based in Vietnam, Incognito styles itse=
lf as privacy-conscious, open source, and decentralized.=C2=A0
Incognito also lets users mint their own cryptocurrencies, Broeksmit says. =
=E2=80=A6 Broeksmit says he thought he could create new coins and then mani=
pulate the market to make them valuable=E2=80=94in his view, a version of t=
he true ethos of cryptocurrency. ...
So Broeksmit minted a series of coins inside Incognito. One is called parse=
c=E2=80=94a unit of astronomical distance infamously misused in Star Wars=
=E2=80=94and another BRA, after his band. A third is called =E2=80=9Cdrone =
algo red 41 coin.=E2=80=9D Then, he says, he set out to increase the value =
of his coins by trading them back and forth, creating =E2=80=9Cliquidity po=
ols=E2=80=9D so that Incognito=E2=80=99s algorithms adjusted the custom coi=
ns=E2=80=99 prices accordingly. Finally, he linked his tokens into =E2=80=
=9Cdaisy chains=E2=80=9D connecting to Incognito=E2=80=99s native token PRV=
, and then to mainstream cryptocurrencies. The tangled result, he claims, w=
as similar to structures seen in conventional financial markets. =E2=80=9CB=
asically what we had here was a derivative. That was my father=E2=80=99s th=
ing=E2=80=94derivatives,=E2=80=9D he says.=C2=A0

What? No.

Despite all his pumping, by December none of Broeksmit=E2=80=99s tokens had=
 taken off, and their prices remained low. He wrote off the project as a wa=
ste of time. But on the morning of January 9, 2022, Broeksmit opened his In=
cognito wallet, and everything changed. =E2=80=9CI was a trillionaire,=E2=
=80=9D he says. He thought his magic had finally worked: All the tokens he =
had traded boasted multibillion valuations. ...
=E2=80=9CI was very scared, because I thought that would obviously draw a l=
ot of attention,=E2=80=9D Broeksmit says. Then reality set in: This number =
could not be right. =E2=80=9CI know I didn=E2=80=99t put in a trillion. I d=
on=E2=80=99t have anything close to that in my liquidity pools.=E2=80=9D Ye=
t, the app kept showing an astronomical valuation for his coins, which he t=
hought proved that he could game the app, or that it was a scam. But when B=
roeksmit tried to trade his parsecs and drone algos for bitcoin, ether, or =
BNB, and then presumably cash them out, Incognito returned an error message=
: =E2=80=9CNo trade route found.=E2=80=9D He says the same message appeared=
 when he tried to exchange one of his custom coins for another. ...
The right thing to do, given the fact that the value attributed to his coin=
s was not correct, he says, would have been to alert his FBI contacts, as h=
e thought these loopholes could be abused by money launderers.

What? No. The system worked. He created some fake cryptocurrencies, fake tr=
aded them with himself,=C2=A0got them up to a multitrillion-dollar fake val=
uation, and then was unable to cash them out at any value other than zero, =
which is their actual value. And then instead of trying to trick anyone int=
o buying them, he went to Wired to be like =E2=80=9Clook at this dumb thing=
 I did.=E2=80=9D This is all fine.

