   =20
      Decentralized manhunt
   =20
 =20

There is a widespread =E2=80=94=C2=A0not universal, but widespread =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0view in crypto that decentralization is good, and=C2=A0law and reg=
ulation are bad. Governments should not be able to tell anyone what to do, =
and certainly they should stay out of voluntary transactions between indivi=
duals. =E2=80=9CWhat if those transactions turn out to be scams,=E2=80=9D i=
s the obvious question, and people who hold these views have a range of dif=
ferent responses. Here are sketches of a few of them:
=09=E2=80=9CCode is law=E2=80=9D: Scams will be prevented by everyone doing=
 their transactions using transparent audited code, with  adversarial harde=
ning of that code quickly working to make scams impossible.=09=E2=80=9CCode=
 is law=E2=80=9D: Anything that happens is by definition=C2=A0not a scam. I=
f two people agree to a transaction, and one of them was lying, well, it tu=
rns out that those are the rules of the game they played, and no one can co=
mplain.=09Economic incentives, social sanctions, reputation, altruism,=C2=
=A0etc. will prevent scams: Most people in most of the world mostly don=E2=
=80=99t do scams, not because they worry about going to prison but because =
it is hard to do scams, no one will like you if you do one, and you=E2=80=
=99ll feel bad about yourself. Why shouldn=E2=80=99t that be true in crypto=
?=09Okay fine a=C2=A0little=C2=A0regulation, but not, like, registration of=
 tokens as securities.

All of those answers have some merit, and they can work in various combinat=
ions. But I suppose you could extend the decentralized ethos of crypto furt=
her, to something like:
=09If someone does a scam, the victims of the scam can form a decentralized=
 autonomous organization to track him down. All the members of the DAO part=
icipate in hunting the scammer, and the more they contribute to the manhunt=
 the more DAO governance tokens they get, and if they catch him a majority =
vote of the tokens can determine what to do with him. And I suppose you can=
 trade the DAO tokens for money, and I suppose the value of the tokens will=
 fluctuate with the odds of catching him?=C2=A0

Replace law enforcement with decentralized vigilantism=C2=A0on the blockcha=
in.
I am mostly kidding but  here=E2=80=99s this:

Kang Hyung-suk=E2=80=99s faith in cryptocurrencies was shattered by the $40=
bn collapse of Do Kwon=E2=80=99s cryptocurrency operator Terraform Labs, wh=
ere he used to work in Seoul. Now he is looking for payback.
In about 10 days, Kang is flying to Dubai, the capital of the crypto-friend=
ly United Arab Emirates, where he believes Kwon is hiding. =E2=80=9CFinding=
 him could be easier than thought,=E2=80=9D said Kang.
The 26-year-old software engineer belongs to the UST Restitution Group, an =
association of nearly 4,400 crypto investors trying to track down Kwon, who=
 is wanted in South Korea on charges of financial fraud.
=E2=80=9CI want to recruit other people to join the search,=E2=80=9D said K=
ang. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a 50-50 chance of getting him in Dubai.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=A6
Another URG member nicknamed HKTrader said he worked for a fintech company =
headquartered in Hong Kong and had blown his savings for a house on terraUS=
D. He said he spent a month organising a Singapore class action lawsuit aga=
inst Kwon and discovered his whereabouts in the country by hiring a private=
 detective.
=E2=80=9CWe tracked [him] down pretty well when he was in Singapore,=E2=80=
=9D HKTrader said, but he added that his group lost track of Kwon after he =
left the city-state.

I kind of can=E2=80=99t believe they=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have a token?

