   =20
      Greenwashing
   =20
 =20

I don=E2=80=99t know, I=E2=80=99m a cynical American, and when I see an ad =
from a company that says =E2=80=9Cwe planted 1 million trees last year,=E2=
=80=9D I assume it also cut down 2 million. =E2=80=9CWe did a good thing=E2=
=80=9D does not, to me, imply that you didn=E2=80=99t also do bad things. T=
he bad things are the reason you=E2=80=99re advertising=C2=A0the good thing=
!=C2=A0But=C2=A0UK advertising regulators disagree:

The UK=E2=80=99s advertising watchdog has banned a series of HSBC=E2=80=99s=
 advertisements for being misleading about its green credentials by not men=
tioning the bank=E2=80=99s financing of fossil fuel projects and links to d=
eforestation.
The ruling sets a precedent for the financial sector, marking the first tim=
e the regulator has barred ads by a bank on greenwashing grounds.
The Advertising Standards Authority said on Wednesday that HSBC could no lo=
nger run the series that promoted the lender=E2=80=99s planting of trees an=
d its plans to reach net zero greenhouse gas emissions.
Consumers would not necessarily understand that HSBC, which made =E2=80=9Cu=
nqualified claims about its environmentally beneficial work=E2=80=9D, would=
 be =E2=80=9Cinvolved in the financing of businesses which made significant=
 contributions to carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gas emissions=E2=80=
=9D, the ASA said.
It said the ads =E2=80=9Comitted material information and were therefore mi=
sleading=E2=80=9D.

I guess the question is what you think the baseline is. =E2=80=9COf course =
we lend to fossil fuel companies, that=E2=80=99s what banks do, but at leas=
t we also plant trees,=E2=80=9D is one view, which would make this ad fine.=
 =E2=80=9COf course you plant trees for PR purposes, that=E2=80=99s what ba=
nks do, but you also lend to fossil fuel companies,=E2=80=9D would be anoth=
er view.

