      Mack! Mack! Mack!
   =20
 =20

Man this is how you end a memoir:
Mack saves his most meaningful short lines for his finale. In an addendum, =
he says he=E2=80=99s been diagnosed with a mild cognitive impairment. =E2=
=80=9CMy prognosis is far from perfect, but my life is perfect,=E2=80=9D he=
 writes. =E2=80=9CI have f---ing killed it. I knocked the cover off the bal=
l in the financial world.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CMy life is perfect=E2=80=9D! Sure you could read about Karl Ove Kn=
ausgaard=E2=80=99s life, but his life is=C2=A0not=C2=A0perfect, and John Ma=
ck=E2=80=99s is. Mack has set the bar for memoir writing. If you=E2=80=99re=
 going to publish a memoir in the future, your life had better be perfect.
Mack is the former chief executive officer of Morgan Stanley, he has a memo=
ir out, and Max Abelson has   a fun review in Bloomberg Businessweek:

Up Close and All In teems with its star=E2=80=99s name. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=
=99ve got to talk to John Mack,=E2=80=9D a Duke University bigwig tells cor=
porate recruiters. =E2=80=9CGoddamn it,=E2=80=9D an early Wall Street cowor=
ker says after seeing him in action, =E2=80=9CJohn Mack just did that!=E2=
=80=9D One veteran tells a big-time rival he=E2=80=99s now No 2., behind a =
new No. 1: =E2=80=9CJohn Mack!=E2=80=9D When he lets a colleague take the b=
igger bedroom at the Dolder Grand in Zurich, their German-accented concierg=
e announces: =E2=80=9CHerr Mack, you are a true gentleman.=E2=80=9D Then, a=
fter leaving Morgan Stanley amid a power struggle in 2001 and returning in =
2005 as the boss, his colleagues greet him with howls: =E2=80=9CMack! Mack!=
 Mack!=E2=80=9D
The memoir (Simon Element, $28.99) serves up a rare opportunity to hear pow=
er=E2=80=99s unvarnished internal monologue.

I think that=E2=80=99s charming. If you go to a publisher and say =E2=80=9C=
I am a former investment bank CEO, my life is perfect, I am going to=C2=A0w=
rite a memoir about how perfect it is,=E2=80=9D there will be a lot of obst=
acles in your way. =E2=80=9CThat sounds like it lacks conflict,=E2=80=9D th=
e publisher will say. =E2=80=9CYou literally want me to write =E2=80=98I kn=
ocked the cover off the ball in the financial world=E2=80=99 at the end of =
your memoir?=E2=80=9D your ghostwriter will say. =E2=80=9CShould you not ma=
ybe tone it down a little bit,=E2=80=9D your loved ones will say. =E2=80=9C=
The book doesn=E2=80=99t just lack a reckoning with Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99=
s role in the financial crisis, it fast-forwards from Christmas of 2007 to =
the next year=E2=80=99s Lehman collapse as if there=E2=80=99s nothing to re=
port,=E2=80=9D Max Abelson will say. But you don=E2=80=99t care! Your life =
is perfect! You killed it! There are so many incentives in the world pushin=
g people toward false humility; it is inspiring to see someone resist them.

