<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is an important time lag in the financin=
g of a leveraged buyout:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At Time 1, a private equity firm sign=
s a deal to buy a company with borrowed money. The private equity firm work=
s with some banks, who will get it the=C2=A0debt financing it needs to pay =
for the company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Months pass, as t=
he deal gets shareholder and regulatory approvals, and as the banks market =
the debt to investors (hedge funds, asset managers, and other people who bu=
y LBO debt). Eventually, at Time 2, the deal closes (the private equity fir=
m actually buys the company), and the banks get the money from the debt inv=
estors and deliver it to the buyer.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The issue is that the debt market might change=
 between Time 1 and Time 2. If the debt market is very good at Time 1, and =
very bad at Time 2, then there is a problem: The private equity firm agreed=
 to buy the company using borrowed money, and it could borrow as much money=
 as it needed at favorable rates in the debt market of Time 1, but in the d=
ebt markets of Time 2 it can=E2=80=99t borrow that much money at those rate=
s, and the deal no longer makes=C2=A0sense, or at least not at the same pri=
ce.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a risk, and it has to be allocated. Yo=
u could imagine allocating the risk to the buyer (it signs the deal at Time=
 1, and then has to accept whatever the cost of debt is at Time 2), or to t=
he seller (it signs the deal at Time 1, and then if the financing doesn=E2=
=80=99t work at Time 2 the buyer can walk away), or to the ultimate debt in=
vestors (the banks sell the debt immediately at Time 1, and then if the mar=
ket crashes the people who bought the debt lose money).<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in practice this risk is mostly allocated =
to the banks.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0At Time 1, the banks give the buyer (and the company) signed debt=
 commitment letters, promising to lend the money that the buyer needs to bu=
y the company. If the debt markets freeze up at Time 2 and the banks can=E2=
=80=99t sell the debt, that=E2=80=99s their problem; they lend the money an=
yway and are stuck holding the debt. Also, the commitment letters will gene=
rally specify the approximate=C2=A0<em>terms=C2=A0</em>of the debt, things =
like how much secured and unsecured debt there will be, what sorts of matur=
ities, and at what interest rates; the banks will have some room to =E2=80=
=9Cflex=E2=80=9D the terms to respond to market conditions (i.e., the buyer=
 will bear some of the risk), but not too much. If the banks agree to lend =
at Time 1 at a maximum interest rate of 8%, and by Time 2 they can=E2=80=99=
t sell the debt at a yield of less than 11%, that=E2=80=99s their problem. =
The debt gets issued to the banks with an 8% interest rate, and they turn a=
round and sell it to investors at 85 cents on the dollar so it will yield 1=
1%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The banks took the risk of the market getting worse, and they los=
t=C2=A015% on the deal.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a common story, and the market for lev=
eraged loans has crashed recently, so this story is on a lot of people=E2=
=80=99s minds. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
29427655.285505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
