<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are other ways it can go. The debt m=
arket can be bad at Time 1 and then good at Time 2, for instance. What if y=
ou are a private equity firm looking to sign up a leveraged buyout=C2=A0<em=
>today?=C2=A0</em>Today, the debt market is rough: Interest rates have gone=
 up, credit has gotten worse, and banks, nursing losses from Citrix and Twi=
tter, are not all that jazzed about giving you committed financing on attra=
ctive terms. What do you do?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One option is to stop doing leveraged buyouts:=
 LBOs are a product of easy credit markets, and when credit gets more expen=
sive there will be fewer LBOs. Another option is to just=C2=A0wait<em>=C2=
=A0</em>to do the LBO and see if credit markets come back.=C2=A0But if you =
really want to do this LBO today, you can sign up the LBO and=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>lock in financing on today=E2=80=99s terms. You=E2=80=99re commi=
tted to pay for the company, but you=E2=80=99ll wait to get financing. Mayb=
e the debt market will get better.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/29427655.285505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXd=
zL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTkvbGV2ZXJhZ2UtZ2V0cy1zdHJpcHBlZC1vdXQtb2YtbGJvcy=
1hZnRlci1pbnRlcmVzdC1yYXRlcy1zb2FyP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0b=
V9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAxOSZ1dG1f=
Y2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7f1294cf" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Blo=
omberg=E2=80=99s Davide Scigliuzzo and Michelle Davis</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Long maligned as the debt-addicted corporate r=
aiders of Wall Street, private equity firms are resorting to an unusual man=
euver to get deals done as borrowing costs spiral. They=E2=80=99re taking t=
he leverage out of leveraged buyouts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Francisco Partners, Thoma Bravo and Stonepeak =
Partners are among those that announced new acquisitions in recent weeks wi=
thout debt financing in place, effectively backstopping the entire purchase=
 price -- in some cases worth north of $2 billion -- with cash from their o=
wn funds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though likely temporary, the all-equity move i=
s a dramatic departure for an industry famously hooked on leverage and cons=
tantly on the hunt for ever-more creative ways to boost returns.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of the firms held lending discussions wit=
h banks and private credit providers, but they ultimately deemed the terms =
they were offered unattractive, according to people with knowledge of the m=
atter, who asked not to be identified because they=E2=80=99re not authorize=
d to speak publicly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The sponsors may ultimately replace some of th=
e equity with loans or bonds at a later date. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSponsors want maximum flexibility,=E2=
=80=9D said Richard Farley, a partner at Kramer Levin Naftalis &amp; Franke=
l LLP who works on buyout financings. =E2=80=9CThey don=E2=80=99t want to b=
e locked into very expensive debt if they think they are going to have acce=
ss to the debt market at more attractive rates in a short period of time.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously the risk is that the market gets eve=
n worse. But it=E2=80=99s bad now, so it=E2=80=99s tempting to bet it will =
get better.</p>
