<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you go on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/29427655.285505/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2lubWFya2V0Y2FwLmNvbS8=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7525cd89" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> CoinMarketCap.com</a>, it will=
 tell you that =E2=80=9Cthe global crypto market cap is $923.36B,=E2=80=9D =
as of about 9:30 this morning. As with any index-y data provider, there are=
 subjective choices being made there about exactly what and how to count. B=
ut <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29427655.285505=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2lyZWQuY29tL3N0b3J5L3ZhbGVudGluLWJyb2Vrc21pdC1pbmNvZ25pdG=
8tY3J5cHRvY3VycmVuY3kv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa029d263" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here is =
a Wired story</a> about a guy whose =E2=80=9Cown [crypto] balance exceeds f=
ive trillion dollars,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=A6=C2=A0seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0hi=
gh? He has roughly five times as much crypto as there is crypto. Clearly Co=
inMarketCap is not counting his stash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, no, I=E2=80=99m kidding, you know how this=
 joke goes. This is the hoary old joke about how =E2=80=9Cmarket capitaliza=
tion,=E2=80=9D in crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0and really in stocks, too =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is=C2=A0fake, or at least=C2=A0<em>potentially=C2=A0</em>fake. It goe=
s like this:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Anyone can make up a cryptocurrency an=
d =E2=80=9Cprint=E2=80=9D as much of it as they want, trivially, for free. =
So I can make up Mattcoin,=C2=A0create 5 trillion Mattcoins, and give them =
all to myself.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then I sell you one=
 Mattcoin for $1. You pay me $1 for a Mattcoin because you=E2=80=99re my fr=
iend, or because it=E2=80=99s funny, or because I asked you to and Venmo=E2=
=80=99d you $5 and told you to keep the change. (Or, it being crypto, =E2=
=80=9Cyou=E2=80=9D are just another anonymous wallet that I created myself,=
 and I sell myself one Mattcoin for $1 in two different wallets.)</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now the last reported trading price of Matt=
coin is $1, you have one Mattcoin =E2=80=9Cworth=E2=80=9D $1, and I have 4,=
999,999,999,999 Mattcoins =E2=80=9Cworth,=E2=80=9D in round numbers, $5 tri=
llion.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Huzzah, market cap.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This joke generally ends with one of two punch=
lines:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Obviously Mattcoin isn=E2=80=99t wort=
h $5 trillion and this is all stupid, a reductio ad absurdum of reported cr=
ypto market caps;=C2=A0<em>or</em>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now I=C2=A0<em>tell=C2=A0</em>peo=
ple that Mattcoin really is worth $5 trillion. =E2=80=9CLook at this fast-g=
rowing Mattcoin ecosystem,=E2=80=9D I tell them, =E2=80=9Cit is already wor=
th $5 trillion, but you can still get in at a good price, I=E2=80=99ll sell=
 you 1 million Mattcoins for just $300,000, that=E2=80=99s a huge discount.=
=E2=80=9D Take some fake sales, add some internet hype and sales patter, an=
d see if I can turn them into real sales.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second punchline is called =E2=80=9Cmarket=
 manipulation.=E2=80=9D The first punchline is just =E2=80=9Clook how dumb =
this is.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s the guy in Wired:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His name is Valentin Broeksmit. =E2=80=A6 A mu=
sician and founder of a band called Bikini Robot Army, in press shots he af=
fected the indie-singer look as a lanky man in his forties wearing shades a=
nd a fedora. His real claim to fame, however, was as a financial whistleblo=
wer. In 2014, after the death of his father, Deutsche Bank executive Willia=
m Broeksmit, Broeksmit Jr. began to leak a trove of documents on the bank=
=E2=80=99s inner workings to journalists and FBI agents. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During his research, Broeksmit chanced upon In=
cognito Wallet, which developed a blockchain where people can exchange and =
trade cryptocurrencies via peer-to-peer payments or through a decentralized=
 exchange (DEX), which allows cryptocurrencies to be swapped directly witho=
ut going through intermediaries. Run by an anonymous team mostly based in V=
ietnam, Incognito styles itself as privacy-conscious, open source, and dece=
ntralized.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incognito also lets users mint their own crypt=
ocurrencies, Broeksmit says. =E2=80=A6 Broeksmit says he thought he could c=
reate new coins and then manipulate the market to make them valuable=E2=80=
=94in his view, a version of the true ethos of cryptocurrency. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Broeksmit minted a series of coins inside I=
ncognito. One is called parsec=E2=80=94a unit of astronomical distance infa=
mously misused in Star Wars=E2=80=94and another BRA, after his band. A thir=
d is called =E2=80=9Cdrone algo red 41 coin.=E2=80=9D Then, he says, he set=
 out to increase the value of his coins by trading them back and forth, cre=
ating =E2=80=9Cliquidity pools=E2=80=9D so that Incognito=E2=80=99s algorit=
hms adjusted the custom coins=E2=80=99 prices accordingly. Finally, he link=
ed his tokens into =E2=80=9Cdaisy chains=E2=80=9D connecting to Incognito=
=E2=80=99s native token PRV, and then to mainstream cryptocurrencies. The t=
angled result, he claims, was similar to structures seen in conventional fi=
nancial markets. =E2=80=9CBasically what we had here was a derivative. That=
 was my father=E2=80=99s thing=E2=80=94derivatives,=E2=80=9D he says.=C2=A0=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What? No.</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite all his pumping, by December none of B=
roeksmit=E2=80=99s tokens had taken off, and their prices remained low. He =
wrote off the project as a waste of time. But on the morning of January 9, =
2022, Broeksmit opened his Incognito wallet, and everything changed. =E2=80=
=9CI was a trillionaire,=E2=80=9D he says. He thought his magic had finally=
 worked: All the tokens he had traded boasted multibillion valuations. ...<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI was very scared, because I thought =
that would obviously draw a lot of attention,=E2=80=9D Broeksmit says. Then=
 reality set in: This number could not be right. =E2=80=9CI know I didn=E2=
=80=99t put in a trillion. I don=E2=80=99t have anything close to that in m=
y liquidity pools.=E2=80=9D Yet, the app kept showing an astronomical valua=
tion for his coins, which he thought proved that he could game the app, or =
that it was a scam. But when Broeksmit tried to trade his parsecs and drone=
 algos for bitcoin, ether, or BNB, and then presumably cash them out, Incog=
nito returned an error message: =E2=80=9CNo trade route found.=E2=80=9D He =
says the same message appeared when he tried to exchange one of his custom =
coins for another. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The right thing to do, given the fact that the=
 value attributed to his coins was not correct, he says, would have been to=
 alert his FBI contacts, as he thought these loopholes could be abused by m=
oney launderers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What? No. The system worked. He created some f=
ake cryptocurrencies, fake traded them with himself,=C2=A0got them up to a =
multitrillion-dollar fake valuation, and then was unable to cash them out a=
t any value other than zero, which is their actual value. And then instead =
of trying to trick anyone into buying them, he went to Wired to be like =E2=
=80=9Clook at this dumb thing I did.=E2=80=9D This is all fine.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Decentralized manhunt</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a widespread =E2=80=94=C2=A0not unive=
rsal, but widespread =E2=80=94=C2=A0view in crypto that decentralization is=
 good, and=C2=A0law and regulation are bad. Governments should not be able =
to tell anyone what to do, and certainly they should stay out of voluntary =
transactions between individuals. =E2=80=9CWhat if those transactions turn =
out to be scams,=E2=80=9D is the obvious question, and people who hold thes=
e views have a range of different responses. Here are sketches of a few of =
them:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CCode is law=E2=80=9D: Scams w=
ill be prevented by everyone doing their transactions using transparent aud=
ited code, with <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29=
427655.285505/aHR0cHM6Ly9taWxreWVnZ3MuY29tLz9wPTYx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B1daa2968" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> adversarial hardening</a> of that code quickly working =
to make scams impossible.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=
=9CCode is law=E2=80=9D: Anything that happens is by definition=C2=A0<em>no=
t a scam</em>. If two people agree to a transaction, and one of them was ly=
ing, well, it turns out that those are the rules of the game they played, a=
nd no one can complain.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Economic i=
ncentives, social sanctions, reputation, altruism,=C2=A0etc. will prevent s=
cams: Most people in most of the world mostly don=E2=80=99t do scams, not b=
ecause they worry about going to prison but because it is hard to do scams,=
 no one will like you if you do one, and you=E2=80=99ll feel bad about your=
self. Why shouldn=E2=80=99t that be true in crypto?</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">Okay fine a=C2=A0<em>little=C2=A0</em>regulation, but not=
, like, registration of tokens as securities.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of those answers have some merit, and they=
 can work in various combinations. But I suppose you could extend the decen=
tralized ethos of crypto further, to something like:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If someone does a scam, the victims of=
 the scam can form a decentralized autonomous organization to track him dow=
n. All the members of the DAO participate in hunting the scammer, and the m=
ore they contribute to the manhunt the more DAO governance tokens they get,=
 and if they catch him a majority vote of the tokens can determine what to =
do with him. And I suppose you can trade the DAO tokens for money, and I su=
ppose the value of the tokens will fluctuate with the odds of catching him?=
=C2=A0</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Replace law enforcement with decentralized vig=
ilantism=C2=A0on the blockchain.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am mostly kidding but <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29427655.285505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29t=
L2NvbnRlbnQvMWE3ZDgyZmYtOTk4Ni00ODkwLTk5ZTgtMDQ4OTQwY2U4NTUz/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBf8fa437a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> here=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Kang Hyung-suk=E2=80=99s faith in cryptocurren=
cies was shattered by the $40bn collapse of Do Kwon=E2=80=99s cryptocurrenc=
y operator Terraform Labs, where he used to work in Seoul. Now he is lookin=
g for payback.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In about 10 days, Kang is flying to Dubai, the=
 capital of the crypto-friendly United Arab Emirates, where he believes Kwo=
n is hiding. =E2=80=9CFinding him could be easier than thought,=E2=80=9D sa=
id Kang.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The 26-year-old software engineer belongs to t=
he UST Restitution Group, an association of nearly 4,400 crypto investors t=
rying to track down Kwon, who is wanted in South Korea on charges of financ=
ial fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI want to recruit other people to joi=
n the search,=E2=80=9D said Kang. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a 50-50 chance o=
f getting him in Dubai.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another URG member nicknamed HKTrader said he =
worked for a fintech company headquartered in Hong Kong and had blown his s=
avings for a house on terraUSD. He said he spent a month organising a Singa=
pore class action lawsuit against Kwon and discovered his whereabouts in th=
e country by hiring a private detective.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe tracked [him] down pretty well whe=
n he was in Singapore,=E2=80=9D HKTrader said, but he added that his group =
lost track of Kwon after he left the city-state.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I kind of can=E2=80=99t believe they=C2=A0<em>=
don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>have a token?</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Greenwashing</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, I=E2=80=99m a cynical Am=
erican, and when I see an ad from a company that says =E2=80=9Cwe planted 1=
 million trees last year,=E2=80=9D I assume it also cut down 2 million. =E2=
=80=9CWe did a good thing=E2=80=9D does not, to me, imply that you didn=E2=
=80=99t also do bad things. The bad things are the reason you=E2=80=99re ad=
vertising=C2=A0the good thing!=C2=A0But=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29427655.285505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRl=
bnQvMTk3ZGJkNzUtZTBhNi00YzFhLWFlZjgtM2I2ZGM2MGI0YmFm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB648e81ff" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">UK advertising regulators disagree</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The UK=E2=80=99s advertising watchdog has bann=
ed a series of HSBC=E2=80=99s advertisements for being misleading about its=
 green credentials by not mentioning the bank=E2=80=99s financing of fossil=
 fuel projects and links to deforestation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The ruling sets a precedent for the financial =
sector, marking the first time the regulator has barred ads by a bank on gr=
eenwashing grounds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Advertising Standards Authority said on We=
dnesday that HSBC could no longer run the series that promoted the lender=
=E2=80=99s planting of trees and its plans to reach net zero greenhouse gas=
 emissions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Consumers would not necessarily understand tha=
t HSBC, which made =E2=80=9Cunqualified claims about its environmentally be=
neficial work=E2=80=9D, would be =E2=80=9Cinvolved in the financing of busi=
nesses which made significant contributions to carbon dioxide and other gre=
enhouse gas emissions=E2=80=9D, the ASA said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It said the ads =E2=80=9Comitted material info=
rmation and were therefore misleading=E2=80=9D.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess the question is what you think the bas=
eline is. =E2=80=9COf course we lend to fossil fuel companies, that=E2=80=
=99s what banks do, but at least we also plant trees,=E2=80=9D is one view,=
 which would make this ad fine. =E2=80=9COf course you plant trees for PR p=
urposes, that=E2=80=99s what banks do, but you also lend to fossil fuel com=
panies,=E2=80=9D would be another view.</p>
