<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Man this is how you end a memoir:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mack saves his most meaningful sho=
rt lines for his finale. In an addendum, he says he=E2=80=99s been diagnose=
d with a mild cognitive impairment. =E2=80=9CMy prognosis is far from perfe=
ct, but my life is perfect,=E2=80=9D he writes. =E2=80=9CI have f---ing kil=
led it. I knocked the cover off the ball in the financial world.=E2=80=9D</=
p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMy life is perfect=E2=80=9D! Sure you=
 could read about Karl Ove Knausgaard=E2=80=99s life, but his life is=C2=A0=
<em>not=C2=A0</em>perfect, and John Mack=E2=80=99s is. Mack has set the bar=
 for memoir writing. If you=E2=80=99re going to publish a memoir in the fut=
ure, your life had better be perfect.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mack is the former chief executive officer of =
Morgan Stanley, he has a memoir out, and Max Abelson has <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29427655.285505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTkvam9obi1tYWNrLW1lbW9pci1yZXZ=
pZXctdXAtY2xvc2UtYW5kLWFsbC1pbi1hbmQtZmV3LXJlZ3JldHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxOTIyX0=
1PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlc=
m09MjIxMDE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d38d9=
8f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  a fun review in Bloomberg Businessweek</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Up Close and All In</em> teems with its st=
ar=E2=80=99s name. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99ve got to talk to John Mack,=E2=80=
=9D a Duke University bigwig tells corporate recruiters. =E2=80=9CGoddamn i=
t,=E2=80=9D an early Wall Street coworker says after seeing him in action, =
=E2=80=9CJohn Mack just did that!=E2=80=9D One veteran tells a big-time riv=
al he=E2=80=99s now No 2., behind a new No. 1: =E2=80=9CJohn Mack!=E2=80=9D=
 When he lets a colleague take the bigger bedroom at the Dolder Grand in Zu=
rich, their German-accented concierge announces: =E2=80=9CHerr Mack, you ar=
e a true gentleman.=E2=80=9D Then, after leaving Morgan Stanley amid a powe=
r struggle in 2001 and returning in 2005 as the boss, his colleagues greet =
him with howls: =E2=80=9CMack! Mack! Mack!=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The memoir (Simon Element, $28.99) serves up a=
 rare opportunity to hear power=E2=80=99s unvarnished internal monologue.</=
p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that=E2=80=99s charming. If you go to =
a publisher and say =E2=80=9CI am a former investment bank CEO, my life is =
perfect, I am going to=C2=A0write a memoir about how perfect it is,=E2=80=
=9D there will be a lot of obstacles in your way. =E2=80=9CThat sounds like=
 it lacks conflict,=E2=80=9D the publisher will say. =E2=80=9CYou literally=
 want me to write =E2=80=98I knocked the cover off the ball in the financia=
l world=E2=80=99 at the end of your memoir?=E2=80=9D your ghostwriter will =
say. =E2=80=9CShould you not maybe tone it down a little bit,=E2=80=9D your=
 loved ones will say. =E2=80=9CThe book doesn=E2=80=99t just lack a reckoni=
ng with Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s role in the financial crisis, it fast-forw=
ards from Christmas of 2007 to the next year=E2=80=99s Lehman collapse as i=
f there=E2=80=99s nothing to report,=E2=80=9D Max Abelson will say. But you=
 don=E2=80=99t care! Your life is perfect! You killed it! There are so many=
 incentives in the world pushing people toward false humility; it is inspir=
ing to see someone resist them.</p>
